          = TBS\n| score        = 50\u201362\n| attend       = 40,639\n| record       = 26\u201311\n}}\n{{CBB schedule end|rank=| poll=[[AP Poll]]|timezone=[[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Time]]}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Florida Gulf Coast Eagles men's basketball navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2012-13 Florida Gulf Coast Eagles men's basketball team}}\n[[Category:Florida Gulf Coast Eagles men's basketball seasons]]\n[[Category:2012\u201313 Atlantic Sun Conference men's basketball season|Florida Gulf Coast]]\n[[Category:2013 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament participants|Florida Gulf Coast]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American college basketball season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n  |mode=Basketball\n  |year=2012\u201313\n  |prev_year=2011\u201312\n  |next_year=2013\u201314\n  |team=Florida Gulf Coast Eagles\n  |image=FGCU wordmark.png\n  |image_size=175\n  |conference=Atlantic Sun Conference\n  |division=\n  |short_conf=A-Sun\n  |CoachRank= 25\n  |APRank=\n  |record=26\u201311\n  |conf_record=13\u20135\n  |head_coach= [[Andy Enfield]]\n  |hc_year = 2nd\n  |asst_coach1=Kevin Norris\n  |asst_coach2=Marty Richter\n  |asst_coach3=Michael Fly\n  |asst_coach4=\n  |stadium= [[Alico Arena]]\n  |champion=  [[2013 Atlantic Sun Men's Basketball Tournament|Atlantic Sun Tournament]] champions\n  |bowl = [[2013 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]]\n  |bowl_result = Sweet Sixteen\n}}\n{{2012\u201313 Atlantic Sun men's basketball standings}}\nThe '''2012\u201313 Florida Gulf Coast Eagles men's basketball team''' represented [[Florida Gulf Coast University]] during the [[2012\u201313 NCAA Division I men's basketball season]]. The Eagles, led by second year head coach [[Andy Enfield]], played their home games at [[Alico Arena]] and were members of the [[Atlantic Sun Conference]]. They finished A-Sun play with a record of 13\u20135 to finish in second place. In only their second year of full NCAA eligibility, the Eagles won the [[2013 Atlantic Sun Men's Basketball Tournament|Atlantic Sun Tournament]], beating top-seeded Mercer in the championship game, to earn their first ever bid to the [[2013 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]] as a No. 15 seed in the south region. Guard [[Sherwood Brown]] was named the A-Sun player of the year.\n\nIn their NCAA Tournament debut, the 15 seeded Eagles upset 2 seeded [[2012\u201313 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|Georgetown]] 78\u201368. It was the third time in two years and eighth time overall that a 15 seed had upset a 2 seed. With a second round 81-71 win over [[2012\u201313 San Diego State Aztecs men's basketball team|San Diego State]], they became the first 15 seed to win two games in a tournament to advance to the Sweet Sixteen. They lost in the Sweet Sixteen to [[2012\u201313 Florida Gators men's basketball team|Florida]] 62\u201350 to finish the season 26\u201311. After the season, Andy Enfield was hired by the [[USC Trojans]] to be the head coach.<ref>{{cite web|title=USC taps FGCU's Andy Enfield as next head coach|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/-college-basketball-mens-tournament/news/20130401/andy-enfield-usc/|publisher=SI.com}}</ref> They won the 2013 ESPY for Best Upset.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=espn|author=ESPN|number=357696378681561089|date=18 July 2013|title=And the Cinderella story continues. Congrats to Florida Gulf Coast (AKA \"Dunk City\") on their #ESPYS Best Upset win.}}</ref>\n\n==Roster==\n{{CBB roster/Header|year=2012|team=Florida Gulf Coast Eagles\n|hdr_bgcolor=#00287A\n|subhdr_bgcolor=#00885A\n|hdr_txtcolor=white\n|subhdr_txtcolor=white\n}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Brett|last=Comer|num=0|pos=G|ft=6|in=3|lbs=192|class=SO|rs=|home=[[Winter Park, Florida]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Nate|last=Hicks|num=1|pos=F|ft=6|in=10|lbs=215|class=JR|cur_rs=yes|rs=|home=[[Panama City Beach, Florida]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Bernard|last=Thompson|num=2|pos=G|ft=6|in=3|lbs=166|class=SO|rs=|home=[[Conyers, Georgia]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Christophe|last=Varidel|num=5|pos=G|ft=6|in=2|lbs=170|class=JR|rs=|home=[[Versoix]], [[Switzerland]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Jamail|last=Jones|num=11|pos=G|ft=6|in=6|lbs=215|class=JR|cur_rs=yes|rs=|home=[[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Eric|last=McKnight|num=12|pos=F|ft=6|in=9|lbs=210|class=SO|rs=yes|home=[[Raleigh, North Carolina]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Alexander|last=Blessig|num=14|pos=G|ft=6|in=2|lbs=181|class=FR|rs=|home=[[Berlin]], [[Germany]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Filip|last=Cvjeticanin|num=15|pos=F|ft=6|in=9|lbs=212|class=SO|rs=|home=[[Zagreb]], [[Croatia]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Chase|last=Fieler|link=y|num=20|pos=F|ft=6|in=8|lbs=205|class=JR|rs=|home=[[Parkersburg, West Virginia]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Leonard|last=Livingston Jr.|num=21|pos=F|ft=6|in=10|lbs=180|class=FR|rs=|home=[[Upper Marlboro, Maryland]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Eddie|last=Murray|num=23|pos=F|ft=6|in=8|lbs=205|class=SR|rs=yes|home=[[North Fort Myers, Florida]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Marcus|last=Blake|num=24|pos=F|ft=6|in=7|lbs=195|class=SO|rs=yes|home=[[Miami|Miami, Florida]]|note=W}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Sherwood|last=Brown|num=25|pos=G|ft=6|in=4|lbs=200|class=SR|rs=|home=[[Orlando, Florida]]|link=y}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Dajuan|last=Graf|num=35|pos=G|ft=6|in=0|lbs=170|class=FR|rs=|home=[[Charlotte, North Carolina]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Footer\n|head_coach=\n* [[Andy Enfield]] ({{college|Johns Hopkins}})\n|asst_coach=\n* Kevin Norris ({{college|Miami (FL)}})\n* Marty Richter  ({{college|Simpson College}})\n* Michael Fly ({{college|Kentucky}})\n|roster_url=http://www.fgcuathletics.com/mbasketball/roster/\n|accessdate=2013-03-11}}\n\nAccording to [[Yahoo! Sports]] columnist Eric Adelson, \"The out-of-nowhere stories [on the squad] are kind of staggering.\"<ref name=Adelson>{{cite news|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/ncaab--who-is-florida-gulf-coast-university--232552429.html |title=Who is Florida Gulf Coast University? |first=Eric |last=Adelson |publisher=Yahoo! Sports |date=March 23, 2013 |accessdate=March 27, 2013}}</ref> Brown began his college career as a [[Walk-on (sports)|walk-on]],<ref name=Adelson/> and was so little-regarded in high school that he does not appear in the database of Yahoo!'s ''[[Rivals.com]]'' recruiting site.<ref name=Forde>{{cite news|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/ncaab--florida-gulf-coast--other-sweet-16-teams-thriving-without-highly-touted-recruits-003147215.html |title=Florida Gulf Coast, other Sweet 16 teams thriving without highly touted recruits |first=Pat |last=Forde |authorlink=Pat Forde |publisher=Yahoo! Sports |date=March 26, 2013 |accessdate=March 27, 2013}}</ref> Starting point guard [[Brett Comer]], who had 24 assists in the Eagles' first two NCAA games, said he had no idea how to play the position when he arrived at FGCU; at [[Winter Park High School]], he took a back seat to future NBA player [[Austin Rivers]].<ref name=Adelson/> [[Chase Fieler]], whose one-handed alley-oop dunk off a Comer pass was the signature play of the Georgetown game, also does not appear in the ''Rivals.com'' database,<ref name=Forde/> and did not know how to jump off two feet when he arrived at FGCU.<ref name=Adelson/> Bernard Thompson, named A-Sun Defensive Player of the Year, was by comparison highly touted; he had offers from budding power [[VCU Rams men's basketball|VCU]] and five other [[mid-major]]s. Nonetheless, he was not nationally ranked out of high school.<ref name=Forde/>\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CBB schedule start|time=|rank=|ranklink=[[2012-13 NCAA Division I men's basketball rankings]]|rankyear=2012|tv=|record=yes|attend=yes}} \n|-\n!colspan=9| Regular season\n{{CBB schedule entry\n| date         = 11/09/2012\n| time         = 7:30 PM\n| w/l          = l\n| nonconf      = yes\n| homecoming   =\n| away         = yes\n| neutral      =\n| rank         =\n| opponent     = [[2012\u201313 VCU Rams men's basketball te